ding evidence for the empirical applicability of Merleau-Ponty's aesthetic writings. The central argument is that for Merleau-Ponty the account of perception is also an account of art and vice versa. In the philosopher's writings, art and perception thus intertwine necessarily rather than contingently such that they can only be distinguished by abstraction. As a result, his account of perception and his account of art are organic, interdependent, and dynamic. The contributors examine various aspects of this intertwining across different artistic media, each ingeniously revealing an original perspective on this intertwining.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aArtxPhilosophy. 0aPerception (Philosophy). 4aPhilosophy : Aesthetics. 4aPhilosophy : Phenomenology. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh1 aDavis, Duane H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Duane H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEmerson, Cheryl A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamrick, William S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamrick, William S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJohnson, Galen A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLocke, Patricia M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNijhuis, Marta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNortherner, Sara J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNorwood, Bryan E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosati, Marcello Vitali, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSwitzer, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4http